In every Friday/Saturday weekend, save one, since May 1st/2nd, the number of new cases reported is higher than the Thursday before or the Sunday after. The exception was Memorial Day weekend, in which this trend was inverted. Additionally, over the same time period, the number of new cases reported was higher on the Saturday as opposed to the Friday 5 out of 6 times (which is where I'm getting 15%). I suspect that this is because of behavioral factors.

Turnout of 2,504 is the highest on record so far and might contain some of the positive tests which have, for technical reasons, not been reported on 07 June 2020 through 09 June 2020. After reconciliation of daily test attribution, there's a more consistent picture: 19,233 of the tests as of 09 June 2020 have been re-attributed to 08 June. The most striking point: Daily positivity rate hit 18.2% as of 10 June 2020 (2,504 positives out of 13,732 new tests), as tests/testing kits have obviously been very scarce in TX lately and too many infections have remained undetected for too long; this opens up likely paths for possible new gloomy scenarios on the high end. Each of today's confirmed case will have worked, traveled and gathered for two to three days and set free a tiny avalanche of new infections in a chain reaction. Therefore, re-re-adjusting to 100%.

It might be the case the spread of the virus, like the flu, is halted in the summer. But while Vietnam has a low number of cases, Brazil has a high number. As far as I interpret the numbers, Texas has been dramatically under-tested so far. With a population of 27.862 mn (as of 2016), it is the second most populated state second only to CA, and it represents roughly 8.5 % of US total population (326.693mn). The number of tests in Texas so far is 721k and represents only 5.4 % of the total tests (13.399mn as of Thursday 21 May 2020). Just to catch up with the average, the number of total tests in Texas has to increase by just short of 60 % or roughly 430k to 1.151mn. As an emerging hot spot, one would rather expect the share of tests to rise to above average in order to get ahead of the curve.

In general, it looks to me like other major outbreaks (such as the UK) follow the same general pattern: first, a massive early climb while testing ramps up as we discover all the cases that had been building up over previous days and weeks. We then have a slowly declining plateau, as testing numbers continue to climb rapidly, but new cases (either new infections, or stragglers from the initial outbreak) get harder and harder to find. The plateau oscillates quite a bit, which I think is a combination of 1) day to day randomness in testing and infections, and 2) the fact that each large outbreak is an ensemble of smaller city- and town-level outbreaks, each of which probably look more like your classic logistic/epidemic curve.
Based on the last 7 weeks of 7-day averages (trending up from 600-800 range up to 1260), it would seem that the cases would be in the 1350-1800 range by the middle of June.
